 and leader coaching.</small></div></div><div class="proof-row"><div class="date">2000 - 2013</div><div class="marker"></div><div><strong>Compunetics - Director of Operations and Engineering Management</strong><p>Led engineering, manufacturing, quality, customer delivery, and high-reliability programs; built quality systems, root-cause practices, performance measures, and process controls.</p><small>Transfer: control discipline, technical translation, process engineering, and risk-conscious execution.</small></div></div></div></div></section>
<section class="section" id="entry"><div class="section-inner"><div class="kicker">First 120 days</div><h2>Earn the right to scale.</h2><div class="plan-band"><div class="plan-phase"><b>Days 1-30</b><h3>Read the system</h3><p>Understand the automation portfolio, COE governance, process-engineering practice, platform landscape, risk obligations, value baselines, and stakeholder decision rights.</p></div><div class="plan-phase"><b>Days 31-60</b><h3>Align the decisions</h3><p>Establish a common intake and selection model using the paired work/assurance view; clarify escalation, ownership, human authority, and evidence standards.</p></div><div class="plan-phase"><b>Days 61-90</b><h3>Prove the mechanism</h3><p>Apply the model to a bounded set of existing or proposed automations; strengthen measurement, close assurance gaps, and coach teams through real reviews.</p></div><div class="plan-phase"><b>Days 91-120</b><h3>Scale the learning</h3><p>Convert proven patterns into reusable standards, platform guidance, capability development, and a quarterly value/control portfolio review.</p></div></div><p><a href="120-day-plan.html"><strong>Open the detailed 120-day entry plan →</strong></a></p></div></section>
<section class="section section-dark"><div class="section-inner objection-wrap"><div><div class="kicker">Strongest objections</div><div class="objection-question">“Has Russell actually led our RPA platform and a regulated financial-services automation COE?”</div></div><div class="objection-answer"><h3>No claim of direct equivalence.</h3><p>My verified record does not establish ownership of USAA's current RPA stack or a financial-services automation COE. It does establish long experience designing process systems, leading process and technical teams, operating in high-reliability environments, building controls and standard work, and placing AI and automation inside real workflows.</p><p>I would treat platform depth and regulatory context as explicit learning and partnership requirements, not as details to bluff through. I would prove fit through a bounded portfolio review and a real automation assurance case.</p><h3>Location and qualification integrity</h3><p>I am based in Pittsburgh and have been planning a move to the Tampa/St. Petersburg region; the four-day in-office requirement is therefore addressable without requesting relocation assistance. My verified credential is listed as Six Sigma Certification, but the current record does not establish a Green Belt level or document three named Lean/Six Sigma projects. That qualification should be verified before submission rather than embellished.</p><p><a href="hard-objection.html">Read the complete objection analysis →</a></p></div></div></section>
<section class="section"><div class="section-inner"><div class="kicker">Questions for executive discovery</div><h2>The questions that reveal the real mandate.</h2><div class="question-list"><div class="question"><span>01 / PORTFOLIO</span><p>Where does USAA most need this role to change the automation portfolio: selection, delivery, controls, value realization, or adoption?</p></div><div class="question"><span>02 / MEMBER VALUE</span><p>Which member-friction outcomes are already shared across BPM, the Member Value organization, and business lines?</p></div><div class="question"><span>03 / DECISION RIGHTS</span><p>What decisions sit with the COE, process owners, risk partners, platform teams, and line-of-business leaders?</p></div><div class="question"><span>04 / PROCESS INTELLIGENCE</span><p>How mature are process mining, task mining, and continuous process monitoring, and where is evidence still assembled manually?</p></div><div class="question"><span>05 / CONTROLS</span><p>Which control-evidence or exception-management gaps most often delay an automation from pilot to sustainable scale?</p></div><div class="question"><span>06 / PEOPLE</span><p>What must the Process Engineers become better at over the next year: process discovery, business cases, platform fluency, risk partnership, coaching, or value realization?</p></div><div class="question"><span>07 / ECONOMICS</span><p>How does USAA validate that projected automation value becomes realized member, employee, risk, or financial value?</p></div><div class="question"><span>08 / SUCCESS</span><p>Twelve months from now, what visible change would make you say the automation COE is operating differently because this director joined?</p></div></div></div></section>
<section class="section section-mist"><div class="section-inner"><div class="kicker">Application set</div><h2>One argument, multiple working surfaces.</h2><div class="docs-strip"><a class="doc-link" href="resume.html"><strong>Role-aligned resume</strong><small>Exactly two printable pages, with verified evidence and direct qualification boundaries.</small></a><a class="doc-link" href="cover-letter.html"><strong>Cover letter</strong><small>One-page problem-first letter centered on governed automation and member value.</small></a><a class="doc-link" href="interview-brief.html"><strong>Interview thesis brief</strong><small>Mandate, tensions, operating model, proof map, objection, plan, and questions.</small></a><a class="doc-link" href="120-day-plan.html"><strong>120-day entry plan</strong><small>Read, align, prove, and scale with explicit decision gates.</small></a><a class="doc-link" href="hard-objection.html"><strong>Hard-objection analysis</strong>